    "ocr_text": "69
K. Aug. 13, 1909.
Mr. W. S. Lunsford, Secretary,
Central Trades and Labor Council,
Reno, Nevada.
Dear Sir and Brother:
In continuation of my letter to you of recent date in
regard to the appointment of Mr. R. J. Horton as volunteer organizer
for Reno and vicinity, I beg to say that under date of August 9th
Mr. Horton writes me. Among other things, he calls attention to
the fact that Mr. C. W. Farrington, who appears on our records as
volunteer organizer for Reno, upon the recommendation of your Cen-
tral Body June 3d., 1907, does not care to have his commission re-
newed on account of other matters taking up all of his time. Our
records further show that Mr. Farrington's commission was renewed
on June the third, 1909. I would like to have the Central Body
officially advise me as to this matter.
Hoping to receive your early reply, and with kind regards,
I am,
Sincerely yours,
(signed)
President,
American Federation of Labor,
(Per F. L.).",
    "summary": "A letter dated August 13, 1909, from the President of the American Federation of Labor to Mr. W. S. Lunsford, Secretary of the Central Trades and Labor Council in Reno, Nevada, regarding the appointment of Mr. R. J. Horton as a volunteer organizer for Reno. It mentions Mr. C. W. Farrington's previous role and his decision not to renew his commission due to other commitments. The President requests official advice on this matter.",

}
